Insect Soldier: Huh? What's this? Something the Alliance left behind?

Insect Soldier: Gwagh... My ears... What the hell is this...
Insect Soldier: What... what's happening!?
Insect Soldier: For your own safety, please remain in your room.
Sophie: But we've been waiting so long already! At least let us have a word with Tindoiimu...
Insect Soldier: You'll see the Princess when she's ready to see you. Please go back to your room.
Hanbei: Hey, what's the matter with you! What're you pushing people around for!?
Insect Soldier: Calm down and there'll be nothing to worry about. Behave yourselves!
Eidatyr: ...Hmph. Looks like we "guests" are really under house arrest.
Sophie: Hmm...
Ru-yi: Ehh!? But why? We saved their Princess!
Eidatyr: Exactly.
Eidatyr: She was Queen, until her big sis came back to claim the throne. Now the two of them are in an awkward position~
Hutchinson: Maybe... But they're family, after all...
Eidatyr: Don't be so naive... The thirst for power goes deeper than blood or feelings or whatever.
Eidatyr: Think about it. When the Queen of the Insect Tribe deals with her sister, would she really spare her companions?
Ru-yi: A-are we in danger!?
Hanbei: I said all along that this would only bring us trouble. Now look what a fine mess we're in!
Sophie: There's nobody on earth who doesn't need a little help from time to time! If they won't let me see Tindoiimu, I'll just have to force my way—
Sophie: Monsters!?
Hutchinson: There's more? Where are they coming from!?
Eidatyr: Deal with 'em first, ask questions later!
Scared Insect Soldier: Gyaaaaagh!
Panicked Insect Soldier: Quick... Find General Jihasaha! Move!!
Ru-yi: Wh-what the hell's going on out there...
Eidatyr: Let's find out.
Sophie: Eidatyr! Wait!
Tindoiimu: ...Drink some water, and eat something.
Toyokuni: Tindoiimu!? What are you...
Tindoiimu: ...None of the soldiers were willing to bring you food, so I came myself.
Toyokuni: You're their Princess, aren't you? What about your orders?
Tindoiimu: ...They're my sister's troops.
Tindoiimu: ...Eat something.
Toyokuni: What about my people? How many of them are left alive!?
Tindoiimu: ......
Toyokuni: ......
Toyokuni: ......
Toyokuni: ...I'm sorry, I can't take you home again...
Toyokuni: Everywhere is awash with blood... This is the work of the Insect Tribe...
Tindoiimu: ......
Toyokuni: We're walking the same paths as those our forefathers took. That much is clear, and yet we can't help ourselves... What cruel fate.
Toyokuni: Go, Tindoiimu. I can't bear to look at you.
Tindoiimu: Toyokuni...
Toyokuni: I know it wasn't you who slaughtered my people, but... I'm not sure that even matters anymore.
Toyokuni: Now, I—I only hope the monsters fall for the trap. Then you and I and everybody else will all perish together!!
Tindoiimu: Trap? What trap...
Insect Guard: Watch out, monsters incoming!!
Insect Guard: Yeah, we did it!
Tindoiimu: Don't let your guard down! We don't know if there're more up ahead or—
Tindoiimu: ...guh...

Tindoiimu: (Toyokuni... He's gone!? Where did he go!?)
